00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:25.040
MICHAEL SHORT: You guys asked
to do some numerical examples

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:26.873
of the stuff that we've
been learning today,

00:00:26.873 --> 00:00:28.470
and I've got a fun one for you.

00:00:28.470 --> 00:00:31.700
A very real one, because
it happens all the time

00:00:31.700 --> 00:00:33.930
in reactors all over the world.

00:00:33.930 --> 00:00:37.970
So to set the stage for
this, hey, suppose I had--

00:00:37.970 --> 00:00:42.560
just suppose, I had a
radioactive cobalt-60 source,

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:46.640
that was calibrated
in March, 2011

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:49.430
to be approximately
one microcurie.

00:00:49.430 --> 00:00:51.747
And it's now October 2016.

00:00:51.747 --> 00:00:53.330
So let's start off
with the easy part.

00:00:53.330 --> 00:00:57.890
Let's say I posed the question,
how active was this source

00:00:57.890 --> 00:01:00.720
actually when it was made?

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:02.570
Because it just says--

00:01:02.570 --> 00:01:03.770
what does it say--

00:01:03.770 --> 00:01:06.460
1 microcurie.

00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:15.920
Supposedly, this was 1
microcurie on March, 2011.

00:01:15.920 --> 00:01:19.850
What does that mean the
actual activity could be?

00:01:19.850 --> 00:01:23.550
There's not a lot of
confidence in that number.

00:01:23.550 --> 00:01:26.830
Remember significant figures
from high school chemistry

00:01:26.830 --> 00:01:28.498
and physics.

00:01:28.498 --> 00:01:30.290
This is when they're
important, because you

00:01:30.290 --> 00:01:31.790
got to know what you're buying.

00:01:31.790 --> 00:01:34.160
So what is the actual
activity of this source

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:35.120
when it was calibrated?

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:36.590
What is our uncertainty on this?

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:44.960
Anyone remember
this from sig figs?

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:46.252
I hope so.

00:01:46.252 --> 00:01:47.850
If not, I'll
refresh your memory.

00:01:47.850 --> 00:01:51.060
It's plus or minus the
next decimal point.

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:57.180
So really, this was 1 plus
or minus 0.5 microcuries.

00:01:57.180 --> 00:01:59.100
So you might have a
1/2 microcurie source.

00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:01.650
You might have a 1 and
1/2 microcurie source.

00:02:01.650 --> 00:02:03.355
They specifically
decided to leave out

00:02:03.355 --> 00:02:04.980
the second decimal
point so they're not

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:07.860
liable for a source that's
out of that calibration level.

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:11.610
So we supposedly have
a 1 microcurie source.

00:02:11.610 --> 00:02:14.610
And I've measured it
on-- let's say it's now--

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:16.680
October, 2016.

00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:20.230
Suppose I went and
made a measurement,

00:02:20.230 --> 00:02:23.890
and it was 0.52 microcuries.

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:26.830
And we want to know, how
active was this source actually

00:02:26.830 --> 00:02:29.497
when we got it?

00:02:29.497 --> 00:02:30.330
Where would I begin?

00:02:34.503 --> 00:02:35.902
AUDIENCE: Look up the half-life.

00:02:35.902 --> 00:02:37.360
MICHAEL SHORT: OK,
yeah, that's why

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:40.040
I've got the table of
nuclides right here.

00:02:40.040 --> 00:02:44.010
So let's look up the
half-life of cobalt-60.

00:02:44.010 --> 00:02:47.290
And there it is right
there, 1,925 days.

00:02:47.290 --> 00:02:58.140
So we know that the half-live
for cobalt-60 is 1,925.4 days,

00:02:58.140 --> 00:02:59.150
which equals--

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:02.610
and I pre-did the math out so
I wouldn't spend lots of time

00:03:02.610 --> 00:03:05.010
on the calculator.

00:03:05.010 --> 00:03:09.130
Activity, how many
seconds is that?

00:03:09.130 --> 00:03:15.000
1.66 times 10 to
the eighth seconds.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.920
And we also remember
that activity equation,

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:21.250
where the activity
as a function of time

00:03:21.250 --> 00:03:26.970
equals the original activity
times e to the minus lambda t.

00:03:26.970 --> 00:03:29.910
The only thing missing here
is the initial activity

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:33.160
and lambda, so how
do we find lambda?

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:34.808
Anyone remember that expression?

00:03:34.808 --> 00:03:37.108
AUDIENCE: Log of
2 over half-life.

00:03:37.108 --> 00:03:37.900
MICHAEL SHORT: Yep.

00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:42.520
And we know that
lambda equals log of 2

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:46.910
over the half-life,
which in this case

00:03:46.910 --> 00:03:55.630
is about 0.693
over 1.66 times 10

00:03:55.630 --> 00:04:04.050
to the eighth, which equals
4.17 times 10 to the minus 9

00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:06.980
per second.

00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:08.320
And so now it's pretty easy.

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:10.000
We know what lambda is.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:11.560
We know what our current A is.

00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:16.000
So we can say that our
original activity is simply

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:22.640
our current activity divided
by e to the minus lambda t.

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:25.480
What's t?

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:28.090
Well, I made an
approximation here.

00:04:28.090 --> 00:04:30.640
It's been about five
years and seven months.

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:34.700
I assumed that a month
has 30 days, on average,

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:37.840
which comes out to t--

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:41.220
I remember calculating
this already--

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:46.730
1.74 times 10 to
the eighth seconds.

00:04:46.730 --> 00:04:50.090
So we plug in that t right
here, plug in that lambda

00:04:50.090 --> 00:04:55.190
right there, and we get
our initial activity--

00:04:55.190 --> 00:04:58.860
what did I get?--

00:04:58.860 --> 00:05:04.450
was 1.07 microcuries.

00:05:04.450 --> 00:05:07.570
Now hopefully, this result
is fairly intuitive.

00:05:07.570 --> 00:05:10.300
Because the half-life
of cobalt-57

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:14.050
is 1,925 days, which is
about 5 and 1/4 years.

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:17.620
And it's just over 5 and
1/4 years since this source

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:18.940
was calibrated.

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:22.510
And we have just under half
of the original activity.

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:25.800
So hopefully that's an
intuitive numerical example.

00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:30.260
Now, let's say, how many atoms
of cobalt-60 did we have?

00:05:30.260 --> 00:05:33.277
Or better yet, what was
the mass of cobalt-60?

00:05:33.277 --> 00:05:34.360
Where would I go for that?

00:05:41.066 --> 00:05:41.958
I'll give you a hint.

00:05:41.958 --> 00:05:42.750
It's on the screen.

00:05:46.884 --> 00:05:48.820
AUDIENCE: Are you
saying the mass

00:05:48.820 --> 00:05:50.870
that we have in the pellet?

00:05:50.870 --> 00:05:54.200
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah, so for
this plastic check source

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:55.690
right here, what's
the actual mass

00:05:55.690 --> 00:05:58.310
of cobalt-60 that we
put in in the beginning,

00:05:58.310 --> 00:06:00.740
again, supposing I had one of
these right in front of you?

00:06:03.795 --> 00:06:05.580
AUDIENCE: Look at
the binding energy.

00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:07.830
MICHAEL SHORT: You could
look at binding energy, which

00:06:07.830 --> 00:06:10.140
is a form of mass.

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:14.690
Or luckily, we've got the atomic
mass right up there in AMU.

00:06:14.690 --> 00:06:17.840
So again, this is a quick
review of high school chemistry.

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:21.250
We need to find out how many
atoms we have in this pellet.

00:06:21.250 --> 00:06:23.010
And once we know the
number of atoms--

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:26.710
and we have the molar mass up
there in either AMU per atom

00:06:26.710 --> 00:06:30.070
or same thing as moles
per gram, pretty much--

00:06:30.070 --> 00:06:33.430
we'll know what the
mass of cobalt-60 was.

00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:35.770
So one important
conversion factor to note

00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:43.240
is that 1 curie of
radiation is 3.7 times

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:46.770
10 to the 10 becquerel.

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:51.550
And remember that 1 becquerel
is 1 disintegration per second.

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:07.620
So if we know the initial
activity of our material,

00:07:07.620 --> 00:07:11.070
using our decay constant, we
should know the number of atoms

00:07:11.070 --> 00:07:12.610
that we had right there.

00:07:12.610 --> 00:07:16.810
So we know our initial
activity, A0 is 1.07 microcurie.

00:07:16.810 --> 00:07:18.690
And anyone remember,
what's the relation

00:07:18.690 --> 00:07:22.780
between the activity and
the number of atoms present?

00:07:22.780 --> 00:07:23.866
Just yell it out.

00:07:27.514 --> 00:07:29.170
I hope you'd know that by now.

00:07:32.443 --> 00:07:33.860
Does this look
familiar to anyone?

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:40.660
Where the activity is directly
proportional to the number

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:44.390
of atoms there, times
it's decay constant.

00:07:44.390 --> 00:07:50.160
So since we now know A0, we
can find N0, because now we

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:52.320
know lambda as well.

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:56.000
So the number of atoms
we had at the beginning

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.250
is just, our
activity over lambda.

00:08:00.250 --> 00:08:06.410
And our activity is
1.07 microcuries.

00:08:06.410 --> 00:08:08.450
Let's convert up to curies.

00:08:08.450 --> 00:08:16.210
So we know that there is 1 curie
in 10 to the 6 microcuries.

00:08:16.210 --> 00:08:19.150
And we'll use that conversion
factor right there,

00:08:19.150 --> 00:08:29.710
times 3.7, times 10 to the
10 becquerel per 1 curie,

00:08:29.710 --> 00:08:37.320
divided by our decay constant,
4.17 times 10 to the minus 9

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:38.760
per second.

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:41.520
Let's check our units to make
sure everything comes out.

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:47.970
I brought a canceling color.

00:08:47.970 --> 00:08:51.440
We have microcuries on the
top, microcuries on the bottom,

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:54.420
curies on the top,
curies on the bottom.

00:08:54.420 --> 00:08:55.860
And we have a
becquerels, which is

00:08:55.860 --> 00:08:58.260
a disintegrations per second.

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:01.450
And we have a per second
down on the bottom.

00:09:01.450 --> 00:09:03.720
So the per second goes away
and the becquerels just

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:06.675
becomes atoms.

00:09:09.260 --> 00:09:13.600
And so we actually get, N0 is--

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:15.310
I think it's something
times 10 to 12th.

00:09:15.310 --> 00:09:19.930
Yeah, 9.5 times 10
to the 12th atoms.

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:24.250
That's the way it looks.

00:09:24.250 --> 00:09:27.790
So the final step, how do we go
from number of atoms to mass?

00:09:27.790 --> 00:09:29.730
Can anyone tell me?

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:33.530
AUDIENCE: Convert it to
Avogrado's number and moles.

00:09:33.530 --> 00:09:34.760
MICHAEL SHORT: Yep.

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:36.920
So the last thing
we'll do is we'll

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:44.080
say we have 9.5 times
10 to the 12th atoms,

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:49.300
times Avogadro's number, which
is 1 mole in every 6 times 10

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:50.605
to the 23rd atoms.

00:09:53.732 --> 00:09:55.190
Then we go to the
table of nuclides

00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:57.308
to get its atomic mass.

00:09:57.308 --> 00:09:58.850
This is one of those
situations where

00:09:58.850 --> 00:10:00.850
you don't need to take
the eighth decimal place,

00:10:00.850 --> 00:10:04.070
because you're not converting
from mass to energy.

00:10:04.070 --> 00:10:05.330
You're just getting mass.

00:10:05.330 --> 00:10:08.120
So if you might wonder, where
did all the decimal points go,

00:10:08.120 --> 00:10:10.520
think of what type of
calculation we're doing.

00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:14.007
If we started off with a one
significant digit number,

00:10:14.007 --> 00:10:16.340
do we really care about keeping
the eighth decimal place

00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:18.050
in the rest of everything?

00:10:18.050 --> 00:10:20.480
No, definitely not.

00:10:20.480 --> 00:10:24.080
We're not turning AMU
into MEV, in which case

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:27.417
the sixth decimal point could
put you off by half an MEV,

00:10:27.417 --> 00:10:29.000
or like the rest
mass of the electron.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:30.690
We're just getting masses here.

00:10:30.690 --> 00:10:33.530
So let's just call that 59.9--

00:10:33.530 --> 00:10:36.340
that's enough for me--

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:43.310
59.9 grams in 1
mole of cobalt-60.

00:10:43.310 --> 00:10:49.950
And just to confirm, we have
atoms here, atoms there,

00:10:49.950 --> 00:10:52.540
moles there, moles there.

00:10:52.540 --> 00:10:54.840
We should get a mass in grams.

00:10:54.840 --> 00:11:05.150
And this came out to 0.95
nanograms of cobalt-60.

00:11:05.150 --> 00:11:08.910
Not a lot of cobalt-60
can pack quite a wallop

00:11:08.910 --> 00:11:10.570
in terms of activity.

00:11:10.570 --> 00:11:12.570
So even though this has
a pretty long half-life,

00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:16.230
as far as isotopes go, it
takes very little of it

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:18.540
to have quite a bit of
activity, certainly enough

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:21.705
for our fairly inefficient
handmade Geiger counter

00:11:21.705 --> 00:11:22.830
to measure what's going on.

00:11:25.340 --> 00:11:28.130
Pretty neat, huh?

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:30.530
Cool.

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:33.620
Now, let's say I ask you another
question, a simpler question.

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:35.570
How many disintegrations
per second

00:11:35.570 --> 00:11:38.060
are coming out of
that cobalt-60 source?

00:11:38.060 --> 00:11:41.690
Let's say we wanted to find
the efficiency of our Geiger

00:11:41.690 --> 00:11:42.680
counter.

00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:45.132
You'd have to know how
many counts you measure.

00:11:45.132 --> 00:11:47.090
You'd have to know how
far away your source is.

00:11:47.090 --> 00:11:51.200
And you'd have to know how
many disintegrations per second

00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:51.890
are happening.

00:11:51.890 --> 00:11:55.840
So how would I get to the number
of disintegrations per second?

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:57.560
AUDIENCE: Convert
it to becquerels.

00:11:57.560 --> 00:11:58.727
MICHAEL SHORT: That's right.

00:11:58.727 --> 00:12:00.680
We'll just take our
current activity,

00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:04.430
which is 0.52 microcuries.

00:12:04.430 --> 00:12:11.420
And so we'll say, 0.52 times
10 to the minus 6 curies,

00:12:11.420 --> 00:12:23.230
times 3.7, times 10 to the
10 becquerel in 1 curie is--

00:12:23.230 --> 00:12:24.880
well, we have curies here.

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:27.260
We have curies there.

00:12:27.260 --> 00:12:30.955
And this comes out to-- what
was our current activity.

00:12:30.955 --> 00:12:33.230
It was in the tens of thousands.

00:12:33.230 --> 00:12:37.910
About 19,000 becquerels.

00:12:37.910 --> 00:12:39.880
So we know that,
right now, this source

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:44.480
is giving off about 19,000
disintegrations per second.

00:12:44.480 --> 00:12:46.340
Is that how many gamma
rays it's giving off?

00:12:46.340 --> 00:12:48.593
Do we know that yet?

00:12:48.593 --> 00:12:49.922
AUDIENCE: No.

00:12:49.922 --> 00:12:50.880
MICHAEL SHORT: Why not?

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:51.797
I heard a lot of no's.

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:57.864
What other information
do we need to know?

00:12:57.864 --> 00:12:59.700
AUDIENCE: Type of radiation.

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:00.620
MICHAEL SHORT: Sure.

00:13:00.620 --> 00:13:03.980
Luckily we've got
that right here.

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:05.890
So if you look here,
the mode of decay

00:13:05.890 --> 00:13:08.590
is beta decay to nickel-60.

00:13:08.590 --> 00:13:12.130
So cobalt-60 is actually
primarily a beta source.

00:13:12.130 --> 00:13:16.610
However, it's used for its
characteristic gamma rays.

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:18.870
So let's take a quick look.

00:13:18.870 --> 00:13:22.920
We look at its decay
diagram, it's pretty simple.

00:13:22.920 --> 00:13:27.870
And let's just say, somewhere
near 100% of the time,

00:13:27.870 --> 00:13:29.970
it beta decays up
to this energy level

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:33.150
and can undergo any number
of transitions like this.

00:13:33.150 --> 00:13:34.620
The only two we
really tend to see

00:13:34.620 --> 00:13:40.020
is, like that one and that
one are the most likely ones.

00:13:40.020 --> 00:13:42.750
So on average,
each disintegration

00:13:42.750 --> 00:13:46.590
of a cobalt-60 atom is going
to produce two highly energetic

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:48.250
gamma rays.

00:13:48.250 --> 00:13:51.240
So actually, what you'd have
to know for this source is,

00:13:51.240 --> 00:13:56.550
despite it being 19,000
becquerels of cobalt-60,

00:13:56.550 --> 00:13:59.970
it's giving off 38,000
gamma rays per second.

00:13:59.970 --> 00:14:01.890
So that way your
source calculations

00:14:01.890 --> 00:14:04.528
wouldn't be off
by a factor of 2.

00:14:04.528 --> 00:14:06.570
Then if you know the
distance between your source

00:14:06.570 --> 00:14:09.720
and your detector, and you
know how many of those gamma

00:14:09.720 --> 00:14:13.440
rays are going through
the detector itself--

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:15.870
which we can count calculate
with a solid angle formula,

00:14:15.870 --> 00:14:17.472
which I'll give you
a little later--

00:14:17.472 --> 00:14:18.930
you'll know how
many of them should

00:14:18.930 --> 00:14:23.340
interact in here, once you learn
photon nuclear interactions.

00:14:23.340 --> 00:14:25.920
And you'll know how many of
them actually get captured.

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:28.500
And that's how you can get the
efficiency of the detector.

00:14:28.500 --> 00:14:30.540
So we've kind of filled
in half the puzzle.

00:14:30.540 --> 00:14:32.790
You now know, for
a fixed source,

00:14:32.790 --> 00:14:35.910
how many atoms there are, how
many disintegrations there are

00:14:35.910 --> 00:14:38.442
and how many gamma rays
you expect it to give off.

00:14:38.442 --> 00:14:39.900
And then later in
the course, we'll

00:14:39.900 --> 00:14:41.750
tell you how to figure
out how many of them

00:14:41.750 --> 00:14:44.460
make it into the detector
and how many of those

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:48.380
should interact in the detector.

00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:50.350
Is everyone clear on what
we talked about here?

00:14:50.350 --> 00:14:50.850
Yep.

00:14:50.850 --> 00:14:54.800
AUDIENCE: Where did you get the
number for 38,000 gamma rays?

00:14:54.800 --> 00:14:58.730
