00:19:45.414 --> 00:19:50.320
OK, how do we set up
the series radioactive

00:19:50.320 --> 00:19:53.290
decay and production equations
to describe this phenomenon?

00:19:53.290 --> 00:19:57.170
So we have a physical picture
of what's going on here.

00:19:57.170 --> 00:19:59.535
How do we construct the
differential equation model?

00:20:02.720 --> 00:20:05.030
The same way we've been
doing it Friday and Tuesday.

00:20:05.030 --> 00:20:07.830
So someone, kick me off.

00:20:07.830 --> 00:20:08.856
What do we start with?

00:20:08.856 --> 00:20:13.640
AUDIENCE: So the production
of cobalt-59 is 0.

00:20:13.640 --> 00:20:20.750
Destruction would be sigma
times flux times the amount

00:20:20.750 --> 00:20:22.540
of cobalt.

00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:25.670
MICHAEL SHORT: OK, let's make
a couple of designations.

00:20:25.670 --> 00:20:27.830
Let's call cobalt-59--

00:20:27.830 --> 00:20:30.500
I'll use another color for
this, just so it's clear.

00:20:30.500 --> 00:20:33.360
We'll call cobalt-59 N1.

00:20:33.360 --> 00:20:36.280
We'll call cobalt-60 N2.

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:43.650
We'll call nickel-60 N3, just
to keep our notation straight.

00:20:43.650 --> 00:20:48.567
And then continuing
our notation pile here,

00:20:48.567 --> 00:20:50.150
you mentioned that
there's going to be

00:20:50.150 --> 00:20:54.620
some sigma, some microscopic
cross-section times some flux,

00:20:54.620 --> 00:20:56.780
the number of neutrons
whizzing about the reactor,

00:20:56.780 --> 00:20:59.900
times the amount of cobalt-60.

00:20:59.900 --> 00:21:06.070
So let's stick our DN,
Dt, equals no production

00:21:06.070 --> 00:21:08.440
minus some destruction.

00:21:08.440 --> 00:21:12.410
Does this look eerily
familiar to any of you?

00:21:12.410 --> 00:21:15.120
Forget the fact that
it's a sigma and a flux.

00:21:15.120 --> 00:21:16.370
Just treat those as constants.

00:21:16.370 --> 00:21:20.220
What does this
look exactly like?

00:21:20.220 --> 00:21:21.560
AUDIENCE: The minus lambda D.

00:21:21.560 --> 00:21:22.880
MICHAEL SHORT: Exactly.

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:30.950
It looks just like dN1 dt
equals minus lambda and 1.

00:21:30.950 --> 00:21:32.540
Yeah, that's exactly it.

00:21:32.540 --> 00:21:41.760
This, in effect, is like your
artificially-induced decay.

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:48.210
So the probability that one
atom of N1 absorbs a neutron,

00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:50.250
times the number of
neutrons are there,

00:21:50.250 --> 00:21:53.130
gives you some rate at which
these atoms are destroyed.

00:21:53.130 --> 00:21:56.100
Just like a lambda gives
you the rate at which

00:21:56.100 --> 00:21:58.620
those atoms naturally
self-destruct.

00:21:58.620 --> 00:22:03.360
So you can think of the sigma
times flux like a lambda.

00:22:03.360 --> 00:22:05.970
Mathematically, they're
treated identically.

00:22:05.970 --> 00:22:09.390
The only difference is, we're
imposing this neutron flux.

00:22:09.390 --> 00:22:12.302
So it's like an
artificial lambda,

00:22:12.302 --> 00:22:14.510
which means solving the
equations and setting them up

00:22:14.510 --> 00:22:16.590
is exactly the same.

00:22:16.590 --> 00:22:17.480
So how about N2?

00:22:17.480 --> 00:22:22.140
What's the production and
destruction rate of cobalt-60?

00:22:22.140 --> 00:22:27.678
First of all, someone yell it
out, what's the creation rate?

00:22:27.678 --> 00:22:30.480
AUDIENCE: Lambda N1.

00:22:30.480 --> 00:22:31.680
MICHAEL SHORT: Which lambda?

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:33.600
AUDIENCE: Oh, lambda 1 I mean.

00:22:33.600 --> 00:22:35.940
MICHAEL SHORT: So what
is lambda 1, this one?

00:22:35.940 --> 00:22:37.240
AUDIENCE: Sigma, yeah.

00:22:37.240 --> 00:22:39.617
MICHAEL SHORT: OK, so let's
keep with these notations.

00:22:39.617 --> 00:22:41.700
I'm going to say this is
like a lambda artificial,

00:22:41.700 --> 00:22:47.840
but I'm going to keep
with sigma flux and 1.

00:22:47.840 --> 00:22:50.100
And just so we keep
our notation straight,

00:22:50.100 --> 00:22:51.830
I want to be able
to cleanly separate

00:22:51.830 --> 00:22:54.920
the natural and the artificial
production and destruction.

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:58.300
And what's the destruction rate?

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:00.372
AUDIENCE: Sigma phi N2.

00:23:00.372 --> 00:23:04.175
MICHAEL SHORT: So you
said sigma phi N2.

00:23:04.175 --> 00:23:06.050
Is that the physical
picture we have up here?

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:12.880
Not quite, because
like we can see

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:18.240
here, cobalt-60 self-destructs
on its own, right?

00:23:18.240 --> 00:23:20.380
Yeah.

00:23:20.380 --> 00:23:23.740
However, that actually is
a correct term to put in.

00:23:23.740 --> 00:23:26.430
The other one that we're missing
would be minus lambda N2.

00:23:30.890 --> 00:23:32.120
So you know what?

00:23:32.120 --> 00:23:35.330
Let's escalate this a
bit into reality and say,

00:23:35.330 --> 00:23:36.290
