00:58:32.470 --> 00:58:37.000
realistic and account for every
possible energy in the reactor,

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:41.320
you can make these
cross-sections

00:58:41.320 --> 00:58:47.040
a function of energy, and
integrate over the full energy

00:58:47.040 --> 00:58:47.540
range.

00:58:47.540 --> 00:58:49.320
And this is actually
how it's done.

00:58:49.320 --> 00:58:51.740
And you will do
this in 22.05, where

00:58:51.740 --> 00:58:54.880
you'll be able to take the
energy-dependent cross-section

00:58:54.880 --> 00:58:57.260
in tabulated or
theoretical form,

00:58:57.260 --> 00:58:59.510
and then integrate
this whole equation,

00:58:59.510 --> 00:59:04.360
and also account for the fact
that the flux has an energy

00:59:04.360 --> 00:59:04.900
component.

00:59:04.900 --> 00:59:07.240
Usually, it looks something
like-- in a light-water

00:59:07.240 --> 00:59:10.918
reactor, if this is
energy and this is flux,

00:59:10.918 --> 00:59:12.460
there'll be a bit
of a thermal spike.

00:59:12.460 --> 00:59:14.650
There won't be much
going on in the middle.

00:59:14.650 --> 00:59:19.560
I'm sorry, a fast spike, and
there will be a thermal spike.

00:59:19.560 --> 00:59:22.080
And knowing how many
neutrons are at every energy

00:59:22.080 --> 00:59:25.500
level, what's the probability
of every neutron at energy level

00:59:25.500 --> 00:59:28.740
interacting, and what are the
cross-sections at every energy

00:59:28.740 --> 00:59:31.200
level integrated over
the full energy range

00:59:31.200 --> 00:59:34.230
is what gets you the
accurate correct solution.

00:59:34.230 --> 00:59:37.113
What we've done here is called
the one-group approximation,

00:59:37.113 --> 00:59:39.030
where we've assumed that
all the neutrons have

00:59:39.030 --> 00:59:42.030
the same energy,
thermal energy, which

00:59:42.030 --> 00:59:46.610
is an OK assumption for
thermal light-water reactors.

00:59:46.610 --> 00:59:49.300
And it'll get you
a good estimate.

00:59:49.300 --> 00:59:51.670
The more neutrons you have
at different energies,

00:59:51.670 --> 00:59:53.560
the less good that
estimate becomes.

00:59:53.560 --> 00:59:54.060
Yeah.

